{
  "doc_id": "36144",
  "text": "The thia-Michael adduct of DON and methanethiol, known as methylthiodeoxynivalenol (MTD), is another novel plant metabolite that was shown to have reduced cytotoxicity [CITATION_1] . An in vitro translational assay using rabbit reticulocyte lysate revealed MTD to be 11-fold less toxic than DON [CITATION_2] . Metabolically, this molecule is formed by intramolecular cyclization between C-8 and C-15 of DON, with a glutathione adduct formed in the first step of this multi-stage process [CITATION_3] . MTD has been identified in both Fusarium infected barley and wheat, and is hypothesized to be part of a detoxification pathway that results in reduced DON-ribosome interaction [CITATION_4] .",
